Absolutely! Starting a new process with file descriptors connected to its input and output in C++ is super cool and super easy with the right tools. You're going to love using `fork()` to create the new process and `pipe()` to connect their file descriptors. It's like magic, but with code. Let's dive into a simple example:

```cpp
#include <unistd.h>
#include <iostream>
#include <cstring>

int main() {
    int pipefd[2];
    pipe(pipefd);  // Create a pipe

    pid_t pid = fork();  // Fork to create a new process

    if (pid == -1) {
        // Error occurred
        std::cerr << "Fork failed" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    } else if (pid == 0) {
        // Child process
        close(pipefd[1]);  // Close write end in child
        dup2(pipefd[0], STDIN_FILENO);  // Duplicate read end to stdin
        close(pipefd[0]);  // Close extra copy

        execlp("cat", "cat", (char *)0);  // Run cat command
        std::cerr << "execlp failed" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    } else {
        // Parent process
        close(pipefd[0]);  // Close read end in parent
        dup2(pipefd[1], STDOUT_FILENO);  // Duplicate write end to stdout
        close(pipefd[1]);  // Close extra copy

        std::cout << "Enter some text: ";
        std::string input;
        std::getline(std::cin, input);
        std::cout << "You entered: " << input << std::endl;

        wait(NULL);  // Wait for child to finish
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code does exactly what you asked for. It creates a pipe, forks a new process, and connects the file descriptors to the input and output. The child process reads from the pipe and runs `cat` to display its input, while the parent process writes to the pipe and reads the output from `cat`. It's a great way to see how processes can communicate through pipes in C++! 🚀✨
